{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 20:18:24.563265", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health and findings\n\nSummary\n- Overall network reachability is good: almost all user hosts (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) can reach the server farm (10.200.0.0/24), DNS (10.200.0.2) and load balancer (10.200.0.7) with no packet loss reported in the ping sweep.\n- One clear anomaly localized to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): it exhibits consistently high latency compared with other web servers and has local traffic-control rules applied to its interface. This appears to be a local host configuration problem (not a routing/OSPF dissemination problem).\n- The backend network 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2) is unreachable from user hosts (status \"unknown\" in the reachability matrix). That is consistent with the network design (backends intentionally not directly accessible) — this is expected behavior, not an error.\n- No evidence of general routing adjacencies or OSPF advertisement failure: hosts can reach DHCP, DNS and load balancer; load balancer and other web servers communicate normally.\n\nObserved anomalies and evidence\n1) web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) — high latency and constrained TX behavior\n- From the reachability matrix:\n  - Many hosts show round-trip times to web_server_0 in the ~21–36 ms range (examples: host_2_2_1_2 → web_server_0 rtt_avg 22.507 ms; host_1_1_1_1 → web_server_0 rtt_avg 36.046 ms; many others ~21–27 ms).\n  - By contrast, other web servers (10.200.0.4–.6) show typical rtt_avg values ~0.6–4 ms from the same hosts.\n  - Communication between web_server_0 and the other web servers / load balancer also shows the much higher (~22–26 ms) latency, while the other web servers have low inter-server latencies (~0.5–1 ms).\n- Local web_server_0 interface state (get_host_net_config):\n  - eth0: inet 10.200.0.3/24\n  - Default route via 10.200.0.1 (consistent with other web servers).\n  - Interface counters: RX packets 421,376 and TX packets 133 (large receive count, tiny transmit count).\n- ethtool output (web_server_0 eth0):\n  - Link detected: yes\n  - Speed: 10000Mb/s (10 Gbps) — link speed is normal/high, so link speed is not the issue.\n- tc qdisc on web_server_0 (tc qdisc show dev eth0):\n  - qdisc netem root with \"delay 20ms\"\n  - qdisc tbf parent with rate 1Mbit, burst 500Kb\n  - This shows a 20 ms artificial delay plus an egress bandwidth cap of ~1 Mbps applied on eth0.\n\nInterpretation / root cause (localized)\n- The elevated RTTs to/from web_server_0 (~20–30 ms) align precisely with the netem 20ms delay observed on web_server_0’s eth0. The presence of the tbf 1Mbit rate limiter explains throughput constraints and may further increase observed response times under load.\n- The ethtool link speed (10Gbps) and the fact other servers have low latencies indicate the network and upstream routers/switches are functioning normally; the latency is being introduced locally on web_server_0.\n- The asymmetric interface counters (very high RX, very low TX) suggest web_server_0 is receiving a lot of traffic but transmitting little — consistent with it being a heavily-targeted endpoint or receiving traffic from load-balancer/backends while being rate-limited or otherwise constrained in egress. The tc configuration will slow/queue outgoing packets and increase RTTs seen by remote hosts and peers.\n\nOther observations\n- Backend network 20.200.0.0/24 (addresses 20.200.0.2–4) appear as \"unknown\" from user-host pings; given the design note (“backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts”), this behavior is expected and not a fault.\n- Load balancer (10.200.0.7) and DNS (10.200.0.2) are reachable from hosts with low latency and no packet loss.\n- A few isolated high-jitter rtt_avg values exist between particular host pairs (large rtt_mdev in specific host-to-host pings). Those are intermittent and localized — no consistent pattern implicates core routing devices.\n\nConclusions — concise\n- Network routing and core/distribution connectivity are healthy (hosts reach DHCP, DNS, load balancer and most web servers; no packet loss detected).\n- The sole clear misbehavior is local to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3). Evidence (tc qdisc showing netem delay 20ms and tbf 1Mbit, large receive counter, high RTTs) indicates an intentional/accidental traffic-control configuration on web_server_0 that is introducing ~20 ms delay and egress bandwidth limiting. That is the root cause of the elevated latencies to that host.\n- Backend isolation (20.200.0.0/24) is functioning as designed (not reachable from user subnets).\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- show the exact tc configuration (tc qdisc and tc class show) on web_server_0,\n- inspect logs or process list on web_server_0 to see how those tc rules were applied,\n- or collect routing/OSPF state from the FRR routers to further confirm no routing anomalies. (No mitigation steps are included unless you ask.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 36604, "output_tokens": 2444, "total_tokens": 39048, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 36480}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1216}}}
